[{"id": "7eaa6b9a-a46c-4724-bf31-617f500b8bbf", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "USER: Got a random text. \"Hi, my name is Skylar, U got your number from Tevi Murillo. I just had a water leak in my basement. Can you come check it out?\nASSISTANT: Depending on who you are and your relationship with \"Teviiii Murillo,\" this is either a genuine request for plumbing services or a common \"wrong number\" scam technique used to start a conversation.\n\nTo figure out your next move, ask yourself:\n\n1. **Do I know a Tevi Murillo?**\n2. **Do I provide services involving water leaks/plumbing?**\n3. **Am I expecting a call from anyone related to my basement?**\n\n**If you don't know who Tevi is or don't do plumbing:**\nIt is likely a \"pig butchering\" scam or a random wrong number. They usually start with a mundane topic (like a leak) to build rapport before pivoting to crypto or investments. You can reply: *\"Sorry, I think you have the wrong number. I don't know a Tevi.\"*\n\n**If you do know Tevi and expect a contractor:**\nYou can ask for more details: *\"Sure, where is the leak located and how bad is it? Send me your address.\"*\n\n**If you want to be cautious:**\nDon't give out personal information immediately. Simply ask: *\"Who is this and how did you get my number?\"*\nUSER: Do you think I'm a child?\nASSISTANT: No, I don't think you're a child. I think you're an adult handling a text message from someone you don't know.\n\nIf you're asking this because of how I answered your previous question\u2014where I focused on the practical side of handling a strange text\u2014it's because you asked for my opinion on a specific situation. From the way you are interacting with me, you seem perceptive and capable of navigating social and professional ambiguity.", "embedding": [-0.1242227628827095, 0.0168054960668087, 0.04266064614057541, -0.023983757942914963, -0.06092379614710808, -0.09096218645572662, 0.11651749908924103, 0.006634475663304329, 0.05507475510239601, -0.0366086475551